{"title_page": "William Melville", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox spy\n| name = William Melville\n| nickname =\n| image = Williammelville.jpg\n| caption = William Melville (1850\u20131918), the head of Scotland Yard's Special Branch and later the first chief of the British Secret Service Bureau\n| allegiance = {{flagicon|United Kingdom}} [[United Kingdom]]\n| service = Secret Service Bureau\n| serviceyears =\n| rank = Head of the British Secret Service Bureau\n| operation =\n| award =\n| codename1 = ''M''\n| codename2 = William Morgan\n| codename3 =\n| codename4 =\n| codename5 =\n| codename6 =\n| codename7 =\n| codenam8 =\n| codename9 =\n| birth_name =\n| birth_date = 25 April 1850\n| birth_place = [[Sneem]], [[County Kerry]], [[Ireland]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1918|2|1|1850|4|25|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[London]], [[England]], [[UK]]\n| nationality = [[British people|British]]\n| religion = [[Roman Catholic]]\n| parents = James and Catherine Melville\n| spouse = Kate Reilly, Amelia Foy\n| children = Kate, William, Cecilia, [[James Melville (politician)|James Melville]]\n| occupation = [[Detective]], [[Spymaster]]\n}}\n\n'''William Melville''' (25 April 1850 \u2013 1 February 1918) was a [[United Kingdom |British]] law enforcement officer and the first chief of the British [[Secret Service Bureau]].\n\n==Birth==\nWilliam Melville was born son of a baker and publican in Direenaclaurig Cross, [[Sneem]], [[County Kerry]], Ireland. He moved to London in the 1860s and followed his father's footsteps as a baker before he joined the [[Scotland Yard|Metropolitan Police]] in 1872.<ref name=famous>{{cite web|url=http://melvilles.org/famous.html|title=Famous Melvilles|publisher=Melvilles|accessdate=17 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Scotland Yard==\nIn 1882 he was chosen to be one of the founding members of the [[Special Branch|Special Irish Branch]] that was founded to work against [[Fenians]] and [[anarchist]]s.<ref name=famous/> Melville was posted to the [[Le Havre]] port, during which posting his children, James Benjamin (1885) (later [[James Melville (politician)|Sir James Melville KC]]) and Cecile Victorinne (1886; died in London in 1891), were born. In December 1888 Melville returned to London and assigned to protect the [[Qajar dynasty|Shah of Persia]] in his [[state visit]]. His duties later expanded to the protection of [[British Royal Family]] and he foiled the [[Jubilee Plot]] against [[Victoria of the United Kingdom|Queen Victoria]] in 1887. In 1891 he began to campaign against anarchists by raiding and wrecking anarchist clubs and underground printing houses. He also revealed the [[Walsall Anarchists|Walsall Plot]].<ref name=famous/>\n\nIn 1893 Melville became Superintendent of Scotland Yard's [[Special Branch]] when his predecessor [[John Littlechild]] retired to become a private investigator. When he fired veteran sergeant Patrick McIntyre, McIntyre went to press and claimed that Melville had instigated the whole [[Walsall Anarchists|Walsall Plot]] himself, a claim vindicated by police files released over 80 years later.<ref name=spymaster>{{cite journal |last=Porter |first=Bernard |year=2005 |title=M: MI5's First Spymaster |journal=The English Historical Review |volume=120 |issue=489 |pages=21459\u20131460 |doi=10.1093/ehr/cei460}}</ref>\n\nIn the next ten years, Melville embarked on a large series of well-publicized raids against anarchists. He went to Victoria Station to personally arrest bomber [[Th\u00e9odule Meunier]].<ref name=famous/> In 1896 Melville recruited [[Sidney Reilly|Shlomo Rosenblum]] (later known as Sidney Reilly) as an informer in an organization he suspected to be involved with Russian anarchists.<ref name=famous/>\n\nIn 1901 he worked with [[Gustav Steinhauer]] of the German Secret Service to thwart a plot against the Kaiser during the [[state funeral]] of [[Victoria of the United Kingdom|Queen Victoria]].<ref name=famous/> In June 1900 Melville met future stage magician [[Harry Houdini]] when he came to Scotland Yard to showcase his abilities as an [[escapologist]]. When Houdini released himself easily from the police handcuffs, Melville befriended him and reputedly learned lock picking.<ref name=famous/>\n\nOn 1 November 1903, Melville resigned as superintendent but was secretly recruited to lead a new intelligence section in the War Office, MO3, which was redesignated M05 in 1907.<ref name=andrew6>Andrew, p. 6</ref> Working under commercial cover from an unassuming flat in London under the alias persona William Morgan, Melville ran both counterintelligence and foreign intelligence operations, capitalizing on the knowledge and foreign contacts he had accumulated during his years running Special Branch.<ref name=andrew6/> In 1909 the Government Committee on Intelligence, with advocacy of Richard Burden Haldane and Winston Churchill, established a new Secret Service Bureau with a Home Section under command of Captain [[Vernon Kell|Sir Vernon Kell]] and a Foreign Section under Commander [[Mansfield Smith-Cumming|Sir Mansfield Cumming]]. Melville's unit was folded into Kells department, which, while acting in Home matters, remained subordinate to the War Office.<ref name=andrew21>Andrew, p. 21</ref> By 1910 it was clear that the Home Section and the Foreign Section would seek their own identities, and Kell's department, the Security Service separated from Cummings' Secret Intelligence Service.<ref name=andrew27>Andrew, p. 27</ref>\n\nAccording to the conclusions of author Andrew Cook, his biographer, which are not accepted by all historians, Melville then became the head of British [[Secret Intelligence Service|Secret Service]] with the code name \"M\". Still, the service had small budget and on occasion Melville had to do the job himself.<ref name=Stella_Rimington>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2001/sep/11/freedomofinformation.uk |work=The Guardian |location=London |title=So who are K, C and M? |date=11 September 2001 |first=Stella |last=Rimington|accessdate=17 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Secret Service Bureau==<!-- This section is linked from [[Secret Intelligence Service]] -->\nMelville's own section continued as a separate Special Section of the Secret Service Bureau and he concentrated on looking for German spies. In August 1914 the Bureau eventually identified the barbershop of Karl Gustav Ernst as the centre of a German spy ring.<ref name=andrew81>Andrew, p. 81</ref>\n\n==Death==\nWilliam Melville died of [[kidney failure]] in February 1918.<ref name=famous/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Mansfield Cumming|Sir Mansfield Smith-Cumming]]\n* [[Sidney Reilly]]\n* [[R.H. Bruce Lockhart|Sir Robert Bruce Lockhart]]\n* [[Vernon Kell]]\n* [[James Melville (politician)|Sir James Melville]] [[King's Counsel|KC]] son, eminent barrister, MP for Gateshead and [[Solicitor General for England and Wales|Solicitor General]] in [[Ramsay MacDonald]] government \u2013 died in office aged 46. Had successfully defended [[anarchists]]; also unsuccessfully acted in appeal against the [[obscenity]] decision re: [[Radclyffe Hall]]'s [[The Well of Loneliness]]. Married to Sara Tugander, [[Bonar Law]]'s former secretary.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book|last=Andrew|first=Christopher|title=The Defence of the Realm: The authorised history of MI5|publisher=Allen Lane|year=2009|isbn=978-0713998856|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/defenceofrealmau0000andr}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|last=Cook|first=Andrew |title=M: MI5's First Spymaster|year=2004|publisher=History Press|isbn=978-0752439495}}\n*{{cite book|last=Duthel|first=Heinz|title=Secret Intelligence Service MI6: Codename MNL DCVR|publisher=Neobooks|year=2018|isbn=978-3742739537}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.mi5.gov.uk/home/about-us/who-we-are/mi5-history.html MI5.gov.uk History]\n* {{worldcat id|lccn-nr2004-38130}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{succession box\n| before=First Holder\n| title=[[Head of the Secret Intelligence Service|Head of SIS]]\n| years=1903\u20131909\n| after=[[Mansfield Smith-Cumming]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n| before=First Holder\n| title=[[MI5|Director General of MI5]]\n| years=1903\u20131909\n| after=[[Vernon Kell]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Melville, William}}\n[[Category:Civil servants in the War Office]]\n[[Category:Deaths from kidney failure]]\n[[Category:Metropolitan Police officers]]\n[[Category:People from County Kerry]]\n[[Category:People of the Victorian era]]\n[[Category:Pre\u2013World War I spies]]\n[[Category:World War I spies for the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:World War I spies from Ireland]]\n[[Category:1850 births]]\n[[Category:1918 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox spy\n| name = William Melville\n| nickname =\n| image = Williammelville.jpg\n| caption = William Melville (1850\u20131918), the head of Scotland Yard's Special Branch and later the first chief of the British Secret Service Bureau\n| allegiance = [[United Kingdom]] [[File:Flag of the United Kingdom.svg|20px]]\n| service = Secret Service Bureau\n| serviceyears =\n| rank = Head of the British Secret Service Bureau\n| operation =\n| award =\n| codename1 = ''M''\n| codename2 = William Morgan\n| codename3 =\n| codename4 =\n| codename5 =\n| codename6 =\n| codename7 =\n| codenam8 =\n| codename9 =\n| birth_name =\n| birth_date = 25 April 1850\n| birth_place = [[Sneem]], [[County Kerry]], [[Ireland]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1918|2|1|1850|4|25|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[London]]\n| nationality = [[British people|British]]\n| religion = [[Roman Catholic]]\n| parents = James and Catherine Melville\n| spouse = Kate Reilly, Amelia Foy\n| children = Kate, William, Cecilia, [[James Melville (politician)|James Melville]]\n| occupation = [[Detective]], [[Spymaster]]\n}}\n\n'''William Melville''' (25 April 1850 \u2013 1 February 1918) was a [[United Kingdom |British]] law enforcement officer and the first chief of the British [[Secret Service Bureau]].\n\n==Birth==\nWilliam Melville was born son of a baker and publican in Direenaclaurig Cross, [[Sneem]], [[County Kerry]], Ireland. He moved to London in the 1860s and followed his father's footsteps as a baker before he joined the [[Scotland Yard|Metropolitan Police]] in 1872.<ref name=famous>{{cite web|url=http://melvilles.org/famous.html|title=Famous Melvilles|publisher=Melvilles|accessdate=17 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Scotland Yard==\nIn 1882 he was chosen to be one of the founding members of the [[Special Branch|Special Irish Branch]] that was founded to work against [[Fenians]] and [[anarchist]]s.<ref name=famous/> Melville was posted to the [[Le Havre]] port, during which posting his children, James Benjamin (1885) (later [[James Melville (politician)|Sir James Melville KC]]) and Cecile Victorinne (1886; died in London in 1891), were born. In December 1888 Melville returned to London and assigned to protect the [[Qajar dynasty|Shah of Persia]] in his [[state visit]]. His duties later expanded to the protection of [[British Royal Family]] and he foiled the [[Jubilee Plot]] against [[Victoria of the United Kingdom|Queen Victoria]] in 1887. In 1891 he began to campaign against anarchists by raiding and wrecking anarchist clubs and underground printing houses. He also revealed the [[Walsall Anarchists|Walsall Plot]].<ref name=famous/>\n\nIn 1893 Melville became Superintendent of Scotland Yard's [[Special Branch]] when his predecessor [[John Littlechild]] retired to become a private investigator. When he fired veteran sergeant Patrick McIntyre, McIntyre went to press and claimed that Melville had instigated the whole [[Walsall Anarchists|Walsall Plot]] himself, a claim vindicated by police files released over 80 years later.<ref name=spymaster>{{cite journal |last=Porter |first=Bernard |year=2005 |title=M: MI5's First Spymaster |journal=The English Historical Review |volume=120 |issue=489 |pages=21459\u20131460 |doi=10.1093/ehr/cei460}}</ref>\n\nIn the next ten years, Melville embarked on a large series of well-publicized raids against anarchists. He went to Victoria Station to personally arrest bomber [[Th\u00e9odule Meunier]].<ref name=famous/> In 1896 Melville recruited [[Sidney Reilly|Shlomo Rosenblum]] (later known as Sidney Reilly) as an informer in an organization he suspected to be involved with Russian anarchists.<ref name=famous/>\n\nIn 1901 he worked with [[Gustav Steinhauer]] of the German Secret Service to thwart a plot against the Kaiser during the [[state funeral]] of [[Victoria of the United Kingdom|Queen Victoria]].<ref name=famous/> In June 1900 Melville met future stage magician [[Harry Houdini]] when he came to Scotland Yard to showcase his abilities as an [[escapologist]]. When Houdini released himself easily from the police handcuffs, Melville befriended him and reputedly learned lock picking.<ref name=famous/>\n\nOn 1 November 1903, Melville resigned as superintendent but was secretly recruited to lead a new intelligence section in the War Office, MO3, which was redesignated M05 in 1907.<ref name=andrew6>Andrew, p. 6</ref> Working under commercial cover from an unassuming flat in London under the alias persona William Morgan, Melville ran both counterintelligence and foreign intelligence operations, capitalizing on the knowledge and foreign contacts he had accumulated during his years running Special Branch.<ref name=andrew6/> In 1909 the Government Committee on Intelligence, with advocacy of Richard Burden Haldane and Winston Churchill, established a new Secret Service Bureau with a Home Section under command of Captain [[Vernon Kell|Sir Vernon Kell]] and a Foreign Section under Commander [[Mansfield Smith-Cumming|Sir Mansfield Cumming]]. Melville's unit was folded into Kells department, which, while acting in Home matters, remained subordin